As PIP was increased, the Z
                        av of the (natural) liposomes decreased and the PDI increased, similar to the effect of DF (Fig. 4
                        ). The data points at 50 and 75 PIP were omitted from the trend since unprocessed chunks of lipid were found in the samples, suggesting a minimum PIP of about 100 is required to fully process the sample into liposomes. The Z
                        av of the (synthetic) liposomes decreased with increasing PIP. The corresponding PDI is presented in Fig. 4. Peak data exhibited a bimodal distribution (Fig. 5
                        ).

Both lipid compositions showed a decrease in Z
                        av as the CPB was increased (Fig. 6
                        ). Additionally, both compositions exhibited a decrease in PDI as CPB was increased, although this trend was much more pronounced in the synthetic lipid than in the natural lipid (a difference of ∼0.2 as compared to a difference of ∼0.05).

As DF was increased from 10% to 50%, the Z
                        av of both the natural and synthetic compositions decreased, while the PDI increased for the natural composition (Fig. 8
                        ). The PDI was not measured for the synthetic composition because the large liposome sizes required use of the laser diffraction instrument, which measures larger sizes accurately but does not measure PDI.
